<p>If you are mixing by machine, put your water on the bottom first. Add your starter (donâ€™t forget to save some so you can bake again), flour(s) and salt.The goal of mixing is to distribute ingredients, develop the gluten, and bring the dough to the appropriate temperature (73-76ï¿®F is common for lean doughs). Iâ€™ll talk about how you achieve that in another post. Your mixed dough should not look like taffy. In fact, the more you mix, the tighter your interior crumb structure will be. Itâ€™s better to gain strength to your dough through fermentation and folding. Put your dough in a lightly oiled or a wet bin. Cover it and keep it someplace between 70-75 degrees.</p>

  <li>Fermentation</li> So, technically this is happening until your yeast dies in the baking process, but there is time set aside just to let the yeast do its thing. Whatâ€™s happening here? Yeast is converting complex carbohydrates into simpler ones. Like college students, itâ€™s all about binging and reproducing. Itâ€™s gobbling up these sugars (which enzymes are breaking into small units so the yeast can consume it), and itâ€™s expelling gas (carbon dioxide for lift) and alcohol (flavor). Its spores are also budding and splitting, creating more units of yeast. 
